description:
The Radeon RX 9070 XT and RX 9070 are AMD's answer to the RTX 5070 Ti and RTX 5070 in terms of performance and gaming framerates.  But the most important thing for these cards will be the RX 9070 XT and RX 9070 price and availability.  In this review we test the cards at 1440p and 4K along with creator, STEM and AI workloads to see if they are the best possible GPUs in this price range.

0:00 - RX 9070 XT & RX 9070 Pricing, Specs, etc.

As an aerospace engineering researcher, I can’t imagine why you’d need such high frame rates in SolidWorks, and honestly Femap and Fusion 360 are much better applications. Modeling in fusion is generations ahead of solidworks, and simulations in femap (and SU2) are much more robust. Additionally, why are you not testing av1 encoding instead of hevc? Hevc, while better than avc, is less efficient than av1, and is also not open source. While rocm support would be great for programs still using cuda, the industry as a whole needs to move beyond cuda at some point, which is how deep seek r1 has made its strides. Hardware agnostic parallel compute which isn’t written in the slowest programming language is the way to go. C++ is nearly as easy to write as python, and is much more performant. While the cuda library is extensive, and helps to parallelize many common functions, there’s no reason you couldn’t do the same in c++, and easy get a 50x speed up on the backend, while also making it so you can run it on any hardware, not just gpu’s, especially not just a specific company’s cards.
